<section>
  <title>September 19</title>
  
  <slide>
    <title>Intermediate Value Theorem</title>
    
    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f</m> be a continuous function on an interval <m>[a,b]</m>,
          and suppose that <m>f(a)\lt f(b)</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Then for every <m>y</m> such that <m>f(a)\lt y\lt f(b)</m>,
          there is some <m>x\in (a,b)</m> such that <m>f(x)=y</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Sign diagrams</title>
    
    <p>
      Suppose we know that a function <m>f</m> changes from positive to negative at <m>c</m>.
      According to the Intermediate Value Theorem, which of the following is true?
    </p>

    <p>
      <ol marker="A.">
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>f(c)=0</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>f</m> is not continuous at <m>c</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Either <m>f(c)=0</m> or <m>f</m> is not continuous at <m>c</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The IVT tells us nothing about <m>f(c)</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>

    <p pause="yes">
      This lets us create a <term>sign diagram</term> for <m>f</m>.
      On a number line, mark all the zeros and discontinuities of <m>f</m>.
      Between each of these points, either <m>f</m> is positive, or <m>f</m> is negative.
    </p>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Using a sign diagram</title>
    
    <p>
      Let <m>f(x) = \dfrac{(x+1)(x-4)}{(x+2)^2(x-2)}</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Construct a sign diagram for <m>f(x)</m> to answer the following:
    </p>

    <p>
      On what interval(s) is <m>f(x)\gt 0</m>?
    </p>

    
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Infinite limits</title>

    <p>
      A function <m>f</m> is <term>unbounded</term> (or has an <term>infinite limit</term>)
      at <m>c</m> if the value of <m>f(x)</m> can be arbitrarily large when <m>x</m> is close to <m>c</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Basic principle: if <m>x</m> is very small, <m>\dfrac1x</m> will be very big.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      Here <q>large</q> could mean large and positive, or large and negative.
    </p>

    <p>
      Notation includes:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\lim\limits_{x\to c}f(x)=\infty</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\lim\limits_{x\to c^+}f(x)=-\infty</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\lim\limits_{x\to c^-}f(x)=\infty</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <etc/>
    </p>

    <p>
      Infinite limits are associated with <term>vertical asymptotes</term>,
      and are usually caused by a division by zero.
    </p>


  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Evaluating infinite limits</title>
    
    <p>
      Let <m>f(x) = \dfrac{(x+1)(x-4)}{(x+2)^2(x-2)}</m> (same function as 2 slides ago).
    </p>
    
    <p>
      Construct a sign diagram for <m>f(x)</m>, and use it to find the following:
    </p>

    
    <p>
      <ol>
        <li><m>\lim_{x\to -2^-}f(x)</m></li>
        <li><m>\lim_{x\to -2^+}f(x)</m></li>
        <li><m>\lim_{x\to 2^-}f(x)</m></li>
        <li><m>\lim_{x\to 2^+}f(x)</m></li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Knowing your asymptote from a hole in the graph</title>
    
    <p>
      Identify the vertical asymptotes of the function <m>f(x) = \dfrac{x^2-4}{x^3-5x^2+6x}</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Note: <m>x</m> is a common factor in the denominator.
    </p>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Limits at infinity</title>
    
    <p>
      Limits <em>at</em> infinity have to do with <em>end behaviour</em>:
      what happens to <m>f(x)</m> when <m>x</m> is really big? (Either positive or negative.)
    </p>

    <p>
      Basic principle: if <m>x</m> is really big, <m>\dfrac1x</m> will be really small.
    </p>

    <p>
      Notation includes:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\lim\limits_{x\to\infty}f(x)=L</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\lim\limits_{x\to -\infty}f(x)=L</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\lim\limits_{x\to\infty}f(x)=\infty</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <etc/>
    </p>

    <p>
      If <m>f(x)</m> has a <em>finite</em> limit <m>L</m> as <m>x\to\infty</m>
      or <m>x\to -\infty</m>, we say that <m>y=L</m> is a <term>horizontal asymptote</term>.
    </p>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Evaluating limits at infinity</title>
    
    <p>
      What can we say about the following limits?
    </p>

    <p>
      <ol>
        <li><m>\lim_{x\to\infty}(x^3)</m></li>
        <li><m>\lim_{x\to -\infty}(x^3)</m></li>
        <li><m>\lim_{x\to\infty}\dfrac{1}{x^3}</m></li>
        <li><m>\lim_{x\to -\infty}\dfrac{1}{x^3}</m></li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Dividing by a power of <m>x</m></title>
    
    <p>
      Let <m>f(x) = \dfrac{3x^2-4x}{4-5x+8x^2}</m>.
    </p>

    
      <p>
        Which of the following is equal to <m>f(x)</m> when <m>x\neq 0</m>?
        <ol marker="A.">
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{3-4x}{4-5x+8}</m>
            </p>

            <p> </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{3-4/x}{4-5x+8x^2}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{3-4/x}{8-5/x+4/x^2}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>

      <p>
        Using this, compute <m>\lim\limits_{x\to\infty}f(x)</m>.
      </p>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Horizontal asymptotes of rational functions</title>
    
    <p>
      A <term>rational function</term> looks like
      <me>
        f(x) = \frac{a_mx^m+a_{m-1}x^{m-1}+\cdots+a_1x+a_0}{b_nx^n+b_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots + b_1x+b_0}
      </me>.
      (<m>f(x)</m> is the ratio of two polynomials)
    </p>

    <p>
      For any rational function:
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>m\gt n</m>, there is no horizontal asymptote
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>m\lt n</m>, the horizontal asymptote is <m>y=0</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>m=n</m>, the horizontal asymptote is <m>y=\dfrac{a_n}{b_n}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>An interesting limit</title>

    <p>
      For the function <m>f(x)=\dfrac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+1}}</m>:
    </p>

    <p>
      <ol marker="A.">
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\lim\limits_{x\to \infty}f(x)=1</m> and <m>\lim\limits_{x\to -\infty}f(x)=1</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\lim\limits_{x\to \infty}f(x)=1</m> and <m>\lim\limits_{x\to -\infty}f(x)=-1</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\lim\limits_{x\to \infty}f(x)=0</m> and <m>\lim\limits_{x\to -\infty}f(x)=0</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
    
    
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Understanding asymptotes</title>
    
    <p>
      Which of the following is true?
    </p>

    <p>
      <ol marker="A.">
        <li>
          <p>
            The graph of a function cannot cross either a vertical asymptote or a horizontal asymptote
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            The graph of a function cannot cross a horizontal asymptote, but it can cross a vertical asymptote
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            The graph of a function cannot cross a vertical asymptote, but it can cross a horizontal asymptote
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            The graph of a function can cross both a horizontal asymptote and a vertical asymptote
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </slide>
</section>